<h2>Solar Panels in Ohio</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Ohio's solar resource potential is stronger than many residents realize, with the state receiving approximately 4.0 peak sun hours per day on average. This solar irradiation level places Ohio in a favorable position for solar energy production, comparable to states like New York and Pennsylvania that have seen significant solar adoption. The state's relatively flat terrain and moderate cloud cover patterns provide consistent solar exposure throughout most regions, with southern Ohio counties like Hamilton, Clermont, and Brown receiving slightly higher irradiation levels than northern counties near Lake Erie.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Ohio can be expected to produce between 1,100 and 1,300 kWh per installed kW per year, depending on system orientation, tilt angle, and local weather patterns. For a standard 6kW residential system, this translates to approximately 7,200-7,800 kWh of annual production, which covers 60-80% of an average Ohio household's electricity consumption. Systems facing south with optimal tilt angles of 35-40 degrees will achieve the highest production levels, though east and west-facing installations can still provide substantial energy generation and savings.</p>

<p>Seasonal production patterns in Ohio show peak generation during late spring and early summer months, with May through August typically producing the highest monthly outputs. Winter production, while lower due to shorter days and occasional snow coverage, still contributes meaningfully to annual energy production. Modern solar panels perform efficiently even in cold temperatures, and Ohio's crisp winter days often provide excellent solar generation when snow coverage is minimal.</p>

