<h2>HVAC Systems in Ohio</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Ohio's humid continental climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences significant seasonal temperature variations, with summer highs often reaching the upper 80s and 90s¬∞F, while winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing, sometimes reaching single digits or below zero during polar vortex events. This wide temperature range requires HVAC systems capable of providing both efficient cooling during hot, humid summers and reliable heating during harsh winter conditions.</p>

<p>Humidity control represents a critical factor in Ohio HVAC design, particularly during summer months when relative humidity levels often exceed 70-80%. High humidity not only affects comfort but can also promote mold growth and indoor air quality issues. Modern HVAC systems with variable-speed air handlers and enhanced dehumidification capabilities help maintain optimal indoor humidity levels between 30-50% year-round. Heat pumps with auxiliary electric resistance heating or hybrid systems combining heat pumps with gas furnaces provide excellent solutions for Ohio's climate, offering high efficiency cooling and heating while maintaining comfort during extreme weather events.</p>

<p>Energy efficiency becomes particularly important given Ohio's extended heating and cooling seasons. Homes typically require heating from October through April and cooling from May through September, with shoulder seasons often requiring both heating and cooling within the same week. High-efficiency systems with SEER ratings of 16+ for cooling and HSPF ratings of 9+ for heat pump heating can reduce energy consumption by 20-40% compared to older, less efficient systems, resulting in substantial utility bill savings throughout the year.</p>

