<h2>Ohio Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Ohio homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) allows homeowners to deduct 30% of their solar installation costs from their federal taxes, with no cap on the credit amount. This incentive applies to the total system cost including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. For a typical \$18,000 solar installation, the federal credit provides \$5,400 in tax savings, substantially reducing the net cost and improving the investment return.</p>

<p>Ohio provides additional support through its property tax exemption for solar energy systems. Under Ohio Revised Code Section 5715.01, the added value from solar panel installations is exempt from property tax assessments, ensuring homeowners won't face increased property taxes despite the substantial value addition to their homes. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation costs and remains in effect for the life of the system. Given Ohio's average property tax rate of approximately 1.6%, this exemption can save homeowners hundreds of dollars annually on a typical solar installation.</p>

<p>AEP Ohio offers several programs supporting energy efficiency and renewable energy adoption. Their net metering program allows solar customers to receive retail rate credits for excess energy fed back into the grid, maximizing the value of solar production. The utility also provides rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, smart thermostats, and energy audits. Their Home Energy Audit program offers comprehensive assessments for \$50, identifying opportunities for energy savings and potential rebates. Additionally, AEP Ohio's Peak Time Rewards program provides bill credits for reducing energy usage during peak demand periods, which pairs excellently with solar+storage systems that can shift energy usage patterns.</p>

<p>Local incentive programs vary by municipality, with cities like Columbus, Cincinnati, and Cleveland offering additional rebates or streamlined permitting for renewable energy installations. Some Ohio counties participate in Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs, allowing homeowners to finance solar and energy efficiency improvements through their property tax bills with repayment periods up to 20 years. These programs make solar and HVAC upgrades accessible to homeowners who might not have available cash or traditional financing options.</p>

